INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - NIGHT

Supper cleared, one plate washed and put away. Cricket alone at the kitchen table with the county tax letter, a legal pad, and a pencil, doing long division he's already done twice.

The wall phone rings. Curly cord. Cricket takes it standing.

CRICKET:
Dawes.

INT. DANNY'S KITCHEN, KEARNEY - NIGHT - INTERCUT

DANNY DAWES, 50, stands in his own kitchen, TV light moving on the wall behind him, remote in his free hand.

DANNY:
Hey, Dad. Roads are clear down here, finally. They got the sale barn running Thursdays again, so that's — Rachel says hi. Kids are good.

CRICKET:
Good.

DANNY:
Yeah.

A pause. Danny looks at his TV. Presses mute.

DANNY:
Dad. Maybe don't watch the news tonight.

Cricket stands there a second, alone in the kitchen.

CRICKET:
Thank you for calling.

He hangs up. Crosses to the parlor TV and turns it on.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, PARLOR - CONTINUOUS

On the screen: the White House briefing room, then MARWANI at a lectern, flanked by the UN flag and a folded blue banner on a stand.

MARWANI:
(on TV)
Tonight I can announce the Lunar Heritage Neutralization Accord. Fifty-seven years ago, one nation planted its banner on ground that belongs to all mankind. Not as conquest, we were told. And yet the banner stayed. It stayed through every apology we owed and never gave.

Cricket sits forward on the edge of the chair, the pencil still in his hand from the kitchen.

MARWANI:
(on TV)
Science tells us those six flags are bleached white now — fifty years of unfiltered sun. Some call those flags of surrender. I call them flags of peace. Let this be our gesture to the rest of the world: we come in peace. We will retire them with dignity. We will return them to Earth. And we will gift them — one to each nation America has wronged. The first, to the people of Iran.

The screen cuts to a graphic. On the left: the archive photo, Aldrin's salute, the flag hard-colored against black. On the right: a computer rendering of the same flag, boiled white, captioned ARTIST'S RENDERING — CURRENT CONDITION.

MARWANI:
(on TV)
In their place will fly the Harmony Banner — designed by a committee of forty-four nations. Not one nation's pride. Not one nation's claim. One planet's promise. The retrieval will be broadcast live, this coming July fourth. Not Independence Day. This year, the first Unity Day.

Applause from the briefing room press corps. Marwani does not smile. He nods, slowly, eyes down.

Cricket's hand closes slow around the pencil. It snaps, one half, no sound but the small one. He doesn't look down at it. Nobody's there to see it either way.

Cricket watches to the end of the segment. An ANCHOR comes back on.

ANCHOR:
(on TV)
— being called the most generous act in the history of spaceflight.

Cricket turns the set off. Sets the remote down square on the arm cover. Stands a moment in the dark parlor.

Then he goes back to the kitchen, takes the wall phone off the hook, and dials from memory — seven digits, then four more.

CRICKET:
(into phone)
You watching this?

DUTCH (V.O.):
(through the phone)
Both channels. They're running that white mock-up every ten minutes.

Neither man says anything. On the muted parlor TV behind Cricket, visible through the doorway: the white rendering again, full screen.

CRICKET:
(into phone)
Tuesday. Early.

He hangs the phone on its cradle, gently.

CUT TO:
